'''Bingtuan Television''' ('''BTTV'''; {{zh|s=新疆兵团电视台|p=Bīngtuán Diànshìtái}}) is a provincial [[satellite television]] station in [[Xinjiang]], [[China]], administered by the [[Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps]]. Also known as '''Bingtuan Satellite Television''' ({{zh|s=兵团卫视|t=兵團衛視}}), it started its 24-hour satellitic broadcasting through [[Sinosat-3]] on October 7, 2007.<ref>[http://space.bizapp.qq.com/800058000 兵团卫视简介] {{zh icon}}</ref>

==Programs==
Its service covers [[Urumqi]], the capital of [[Xinjiang]], and many regions under the [[Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps|XPCC]], and several other [[province]]s in [[People's Republic of China|China]]. On July 1, 2008, Bingtuan Television was rendered meliorative, with the generality modified by concentrating on music programs, in an effort to become the top youth music channel in [[China]]. However, after the [[July 2009 Ürümqi riots|July 5 Urumqi riots]], [[State Administration of Radio, Film, and Television]] demanded for BTTV to rectify its contents;<ref>[http://www.hzdtv.com/motif/dtvArticleView.action?selectArticleId=1005070&selectMotifId=1000473 82频道节目调整公告] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712233826/http://www.hzdtv.com/motif/dtvArticleView.action?selectArticleId=1005070&selectMotifId=1000473 |date=July 12, 2011 }}，杭州华数在线 {{zh icon}}</ref> BTTV had to cancel the previously planned entertainment-centered projects made by the specialized program production company based in [[Urumqi]] and [[Beijing]], routinely rebroadcasting [[CCTV-1]], the primary channel of [[China Central Television]]. BTTV only keep some of its original programs, sucu as the ''Bingtuan News'' and [[soap operas]].

