{{Infobox scientist | name = Edith Fanta | birth_name = | birth_date = 1943 | death_date = 7 May 2008 | nationality = Brazil | fields = Marine Biology | workplaces = Federal University of Paraná State | alma_mater = University of Bristol [[São Paulo State University]] }}
'''Edith Susana Elisabeth Fanta''' was a Brazilian [[Antarctic]] researcher, best known for her work on preserving and protecting Antarctica.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|date=2009-07-01|title=Obituary|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/article_S0032247409008195|journal=Polar Record|volume=45|issue=03|pages=288–288|doi=10.1017/S0032247409008195|issn=1475-3057}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Fanta was born in São Paulo, Brazil in 1943.<ref name=":0" /> She received her Masters (1970) and PhD (1972) degrees from the [[University of São Paulo]] in the field of Zoology.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://classic.ipy.org/international/joint-committee/fanta.pdf|title=Nomination for Scientific Committees or Equivalent|last=|first=|date=|website=classic.ipy.org/|publisher=International Council for Science|access-date=}}</ref>
==Career and impact== Fanta undertook post-doctoral research at the Institute of Radiation and Environment in Munich, Germany (1974–76), and at the [[University of Bristol]], UK.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://archive.ccamlr.org/ccamlr_science/Vol-15-2008/00obituary.pdf|title=Obituary|last=Kawall|first=Helena|last2=Bacila|first2=Metry|date=2008|website=archive.ccamlr.org/|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> She then returned to Brazil to the Fisheries Institute at [[São Paulo State University]], before taking on a professorship at the Federal University of Paraná State (UFPR) in the Center of Marine Studies in 1980. She later moved to the Department of Cell Biology at the UFPR.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2" />
Fanta was part of the Brazilian Antarctic programme for 25 years, since its inception in 1983.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2" /> She became an international leader in the Antarctic science through her research on the behaviour, physiology and morphology of Antarctic fish, publishing 58 peer-reviewed papers. She represented Brazil in many international Antarctic fora, including in the [[Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research]] (SCAR) Biology/ Life Sciences Standing Scientific Group<ref name=":2" /> and in the [[Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources]] (CCAMLR) since 1992.<ref name=":1" /> For over ten years, she made valuable contributions from the early 1990s to the [[Antarctic Treaty System]] as member of the SCAR Group of Specialists on Environmental Affairs and Conservation.<ref name=":0" /> She also served as a member of the [[International Polar Year]] (IPY) Joint Committee and led a project as part of IPY (2007-2008).<ref name=":0" /> Her dedication to science-based conservation and management of Antarctic marine resources led to her election as Chair of the Scientific Committee of the Commission for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources (CCAMLR) where she served from 2005 until her death in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ats.aq/devPH/noticia_completa.aspx?IdNews=13&lang=e|title=Dr. Edith S. Fanta|date=2008|website=ats.aq|publisher=Secretariat of the Antarctic Treaty|access-date=2016-06-24}}</ref>
