{{Infobox election | election_name = Republic of the Congo presidential election, 2002 | country = Republic of the Congo | type = presidential | ongoing = no | colours = yes | previous_election = Republic of the Congo presidential election, 1992 | previous_year = 1992 | next_election = Republic of the Congo presidential election, 2009 | next_year = 2009 | election_date = 10 March 2002 | turnout = 74.7% | colour1 = DC241f | image1 = [[File:Denis Sassou Nguesso 2014.png|100px]] | nominee1 = [[Denis Sassou-Nguesso]] | party1 = Congolese Labour Party | popular_vote1 = | percentage1 = 89.4% | colour2 = ff6600 | image2 = [[File:No image.png|100px]] | nominee2 = [[Joseph Kignoumbi Kia Mboungou]] | party2 = Pan-African Union for Social Democracy | popular_vote2 = | percentage2 = 2.8% | map_image = | map_size = | map_caption = | title = [[List of heads of state of the Republic of the Congo|President]] | before_election = [[Denis Sassou-Nguesso]] | before_party = Congolese Labour Party | after_election = [[Denis Sassou-Nguesso]] | after_party = Congolese Labour Party }} {{Politics of the Republic of the Congo}}
A '''presidential election''' was held in the [[Republic of the Congo]] on 10 March 2002. This followed the country's second [[Republic of the Congo Civil War (1997-99)|civil war (1997-1999)]], which returned [[Denis Sassou Nguesso]] to power, and a subsequent transitional period, in which a new constitution was written and [[Republic of the Congo constitutional referendum, 2002|approved by referendum]] in January 2002.
The election lacked meaningful opposition participation, as the main opposition leaders&mdash;particularly former President [[Pascal Lissouba]] of the [[Pan-African Union for Social Democracy]] (UPADS) and former Prime Minister [[Bernard Kolélas]] of the [[Congolese Movement for Democracy and Integral Development]] (MCDDI)&mdash;were in exile, prevented from returning to Congo by legal convictions and sentences that were handed down ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]''. The only important opposition figure left to contest the election was former Prime Minister [[André Milongo]] of the [[Union for Democracy and the Republic (Congo)|Union for Democracy and the Republic]] (UDR), but he withdrew a few days before the election, claiming that it would be fraudulent.
Sassou Nguesso, standing as the candidate of his own [[Congolese Labour Party]] (PCT) and a coalition, the [[United Democratic Forces (Congo)|United Democratic Forces]] (FDU), was overwhelmingly elected, receiving nearly 90% of the vote against a field of minor challengers. He was sworn in on 14 August 2002 in a ceremony at the Palace of Congress in [[Brazzaville]] in the presence of seven other African heads of state.<ref>Richard Songo, [http://www.congopage.com/article479.html "Le putschiste Sassou devient officiellement "président élu""], Congopage.com, August 14, 2002 {{fr icon}}.</ref>
Provisional results were announced by the Minister of the Interior, [[Pierre Oba]], on 13 March 2002; final results, which were only slightly different from the provisional results, were proclaimed by the Supreme Court on 29 March. There were 1,733,943 registered voters at the time of the election, 1,295,319 of whom voted. 92,706 votes were invalid, leaving 1,202,611 valid votes. 1,075,247 of those votes went to Sassou Nguesso.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120226070154/http://www.brazzaville-adiac.com/index.php?action=depeche&dep_id=713&oldaction=liste&regpay_id=0&them_id=0&cat_id=0&ss_cat_id=0&LISTE_FROM=60&select_month=0&select_year=0 "La Cour suprême du Congo proclame les résultats définitifs du scrutin présidentiel"], ''Les Dépêches de Brazzaville'', 29 March 2002 {{fr icon}}.</ref>
