{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}

The '''Unity Movement for Democracy''' ({{lang-pt|Movimento de Unidade para a Democracia}}, '''MUD''') was a political party in [[Guinea-Bissau]].

==History==
The MUD was established on 6 June 1990 by [[Filinto Vaz Martins]], a former member of the ruling [[African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde|PAIGC]], and was the second party established after multi-party democracy was introduced.<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p281</ref> It joined the [[Union for Change]] alliance, which won six seats in the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1994|1994 general elections]], although MUD did not receive any of the seats.<ref name=M2>Mendy, p282</ref>

The Union for Change was reduced to three seats in the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1999–2000|1999–2000 general elections]], and lost them all in the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]], after which the MUD became inactive.<ref name=M2/>

